The paper deals with distributed function computation over a network, which involves information exchange between nodes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves analysis of the network structure and computation time, which are relevant to the Networked Systems (cs.NI) and Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also involves analysis of the accuracy and confidence of the computation, which are relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of concentration inequalities and data processing inequalities, which are relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
